How to build dashboard pages that follow a consistent structure — and a CLI that generates them in one command.

Every dashboard starts small. A users page, an orders page, maybe a products page. Each one gets built by a different developer, at a different time, with slightly different patterns.
Six months later, you have twelve management pages. Some keep state in the parent component, some push it into hooks. Some extract the actions menu, some inline it. Some define columns in the component, some in a separate file. The “pattern” is whatever the last developer did.
This article shows a way out: a standardised management page pattern that’s consistent enough to automate with a CLI generator.
The demo
Everything in this article comes from a working Next.js app:

• Repo: github.com/sandylib/dashboard-page-pattern

• DataTable library: @sandylib27/react-ag-datatable

• Architecture: feature-based-frontend
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Clone it, run npm install && npm run dev, and you'll see a dashboard with two management pages -- one built by hand, one generated by the CLI.
git clone https://github.com/sandylib/dashboard-page-pattern.git
cd dashboard-page-pattern
npm install
npm run dev
1. The architecture
The demo follows a 4-layer architecture where imports only flow downward:
app/ → Routes and composition root
↓
features/ → UI components, hooks, business logic
↓
domains/ → Data layer: types, API calls, thin data hooks
↓
core/ → Shared infrastructure: constants, configEach layer has a single responsibility:

• app/ is the composition root. Route pages import a feature component and render it. No business logic.

• features/ owns all React components and hooks that combine data with UI state.

• domains/ owns data types, API functions, and thin hooks that return { data, isLoading, refetch }. No UI code.

• core/ owns shared constants like query keys. Imported by everyone, imports nothing above it.
The critical rule: features import from domains, but domains never import from features. This is what makes the pattern portable — the same domain hook works whether it’s called from a management page, a dashboard widget, or a search dropdown.

2. The management page pattern
Every management page in the dashboard follows this folder structure:
features/dashboard/ui/<domain>/
├── <Domain>Management.tsx # Render orchestrator
├── hooks/
│ └── use<Domain>Management.ts # Composes domain hook + UI state
└── table/
├── use<Singular>Columns.tsx # Column definitions
└── <Singular>ActionsMenu.tsx # Row actions dropdownFour files, each with a clear responsibility.
The Management component — pure render
The top-level component is a thin orchestrator. It calls the management hook for data, the columns hook for column definitions, and renders the DataTable:
// features/dashboard/ui/orders/OrdersManagement.tsx
'use client';
import { DataTable } from '@sandylib27/react-ag-datatable';
import type { OrderDto } from '@/domains/orders';
import { useOrdersManagement } from './hooks/useOrdersManagement';
import { useOrderColumns } from './table/useOrderColumns';
export function OrdersManagement() {
const { data, isLoading, handleEdit, handleDelete } = useOrdersManagement();
const columns = useOrderColumns({ onEdit: handleEdit, onDelete: handleDelete });
if (isLoading) {
return <div className="p-8 text-muted">Loading orders...</div>;
}
return (
<div className="space-y-4">
<div>
<h1 className="text-2xl font-semibold text-foreground">Orders</h1>
<p className="text-sm text-muted">
Manage customer orders, track status, and review order history.
</p>
</div>
<DataTable<OrderDto>
data={data}
columns={columns}
enableSorting
enableColumnFilter
enableColumnMenu
enableExport
exportFileName="orders"
pagination
pageSize={10}
hoverable
bordered
/>
</div>
);
}Notice what’s not here: no useState, no mutation logic, no API calls. The component only renders.
The management hook — data + UI state
The hook composes the domain’s data hook with page-level UI concerns:
// features/dashboard/ui/orders/hooks/useOrdersManagement.ts
'use client';
import { useOrders, type OrderDto } from '@/domains/orders';
export function useOrdersManagement() {
const { data, isLoading, refetch } = useOrders();
const handleEdit = (row: OrderDto) => {
console.log('Edit order:', row.id);
};
const handleDelete = (row: OrderDto) => {
console.log('Delete order:', row.id);
};
return { data, isLoading, refetch, handleEdit, handleDelete };
}In a real app, this hook would hold dialog state (editTarget, deleteTarget), mutation calls, and toast notifications. The scaffold keeps it minimal -- developers add complexity as needed.
The columns hook — typed column definitions
Column definitions live in their own hook, separated from the component:
// features/dashboard/ui/orders/table/useOrderColumns.tsx
'use client';
import { useMemo } from 'react';
import type { ColDef } from '@sandylib27/react-ag-datatable';
import type { OrderDto } from '@/domains/orders';
import { OrderActionsMenu } from './OrderActionsMenu';
export function useOrderColumns({ onEdit, onDelete }) {
return useMemo((): ColDef<OrderDto>[] => [
{
field: 'id',
headerName: 'Order ID',
maxWidth: 120,
cellRenderer: (params) => (
<span className="font-medium text-foreground">{params.value}</span>
),
},
{ field: 'customer', headerName: 'Customer' },
{
field: 'status',
headerName: 'Status',
maxWidth: 140,
cellRenderer: (params) => (
<span className="rounded-full px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium capitalize ...">
{params.value}
</span>
),
},
{
field: 'total',
headerName: 'Total',
type: 'numericColumn',
valueFormatter: (p) =>
`$${p.value?.toLocaleString('en-US', { minimumFractionDigits: 2 })}`,
},
{
colId: 'actions',
headerName: '',
sortable: false,
filter: false,
maxWidth: 60,
cellRenderer: (params) =>
params.data ? (
<OrderActionsMenu row={params.data} onEdit={onEdit} onDelete={onDelete} />
) : null,
},
], [onEdit, onDelete]);
}The actions menu — row-level interactions
Each row gets a dropdown with edit/delete actions. Because the menu is rendered inside an AG Grid cell, the dropdown should be portaled to document.body; otherwise grid overflow can clip the menu.
// features/dashboard/ui/orders/table/OrderActionsMenu.tsx
'use client';
import { useState, useRef, useEffect } from 'react';
import { createPortal } from 'react-dom';
import { MoreHorizontal, Pencil, Trash2 } from 'lucide-react';
import type { OrderDto } from '@/domains/orders';
export function OrderActionsMenu({ row, onEdit, onDelete }) {
const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);
const [position, setPosition] = useState(null);
const triggerRef = useRef(null);
const menuRef = useRef(null);
useEffect(() => {
if (!open) return;
const updatePosition = () => {
const rect = triggerRef.current?.getBoundingClientRect();
if (!rect) return;
setPosition({
top: rect.bottom + 4,
left: Math.min(rect.right - 144, window.innerWidth - 152),
});
};
const closeOnOutsideClick = (event) => {
const target = event.target;
if (
triggerRef.current?.contains(target) ||
menuRef.current?.contains(target)
) {
return;
}
setOpen(false);
};
updatePosition();
document.addEventListener('mousedown', closeOnOutsideClick);
window.addEventListener('resize', updatePosition);
window.addEventListener('scroll', updatePosition, true);
return () => {
document.removeEventListener('mousedown', closeOnOutsideClick);
window.removeEventListener('resize', updatePosition);
window.removeEventListener('scroll', updatePosition, true);
};
}, [open]);
const menu = open && position
? createPortal(
<div ref={menuRef} className="fixed z-50 w-36 rounded-lg border ..." style={position}>
<button onClick={() => { onEdit(row); setOpen(false); }}>
<Pencil size={14} /> Edit
</button>
<button onClick={() => { onDelete(row); setOpen(false); }}>
<Trash2 size={14} /> Delete
</button>
</div>,
document.body,
)
: null;
return (
<div onClick={(e) => e.stopPropagation()} onMouseDown={(e) => e.stopPropagation()}>
<button ref={triggerRef} onClick={() => setOpen((current) => !current)}>
<MoreHorizontal size={16} />
</button>
{menu}
</div>
);
}This is one of the few implementation details worth standardising. Row actions usually live inside scrollable table containers; a portal keeps the dropdown visible and avoids layout hacks like changing AG Grid overflow styles globally.
The domain layer — data only
The domain provides the data shape and a thin hook:
// domains/orders/types/orders.types.ts
export interface OrderDto {
id: string;
customer: string;
status: 'pending' | 'processing' | 'shipped' | 'delivered' | 'cancelled';
total: number;
items: number;
date: string;
}// domains/orders/hooks/useOrders.ts
export function useOrders() {
// In production: useQuery({ queryKey: QUERY_KEYS.ORDERS, queryFn: ordersApi.getAll })
const [data, setData] = useState<OrderDto[]>([]);
const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
const fetchOrders = useCallback(async () => {
setIsLoading(true);
const result = await ordersApi.getAll();
setData(result);
setIsLoading(false);
}, []);
useEffect(() => { fetchOrders(); }, [fetchOrders]);
return { data, isLoading, refetch: fetchOrders };
}The hook returns the same shape as React Query’s useQuery -- { data, isLoading, refetch }. When you migrate to a real API, you swap the implementation but the interface stays the same.

3. The route page
The route page is one line of composition:
// app/orders/page.tsx
import { OrdersManagement } from '@/features/dashboard/ui/orders/OrdersManagement';
export default function OrdersPage() {
return <OrdersManagement />;
}No business logic in app/. The route just picks which feature to render.

4. From pattern to generator
Once you have a consistent pattern, you can automate it. The demo includes a CLI generator at scripts/gen-dash-page.mjs that takes a domain name and produces the full page scaffold:
npm run gen:dash-page -- customersOutput:
Dashboard Management Page Generator
Domain: customers
Pascal: Customers Camel: customers Upper: CUSTOMERS
Human: Customers Singular: Customer
Summary
Created (6):
+ features/dashboard/ui/customers/CustomersManagement.tsx
+ features/dashboard/ui/customers/hooks/useCustomersManagement.ts
+ features/dashboard/ui/customers/table/useCustomerColumns.tsx
+ features/dashboard/ui/customers/table/CustomerActionsMenu.tsx
+ app/customers/page.tsx
+ domains/customers/index.ts
Modified (2):
~ features/dashboard/ui/layout/nav-items.ts
~ core/constants/query-keys.tsHow it works
The generator derives all names from the kebab-case input:
InputDerivedUsed forcustomersCustomersComponent namescustomerscustomersFile paths, routescustomersCUSTOMERSQuery key constantcustomersCustomerSingular (row-level types)customersCustomersHuman-readable labels
Multi-word domains work too: media-assets becomes MediaAssets, mediaAssets, MEDIA_ASSETS, MediaAsset.
Append operations
Besides creating files, the generator modifies two existing files:
nav-items.ts -- adds a sidebar entry:
{ label: 'Customers', icon: 'file-text', href: '/customers' },query-keys.ts -- adds a query key:
CUSTOMERS: ['customers'] as const,Both operations are idempotent — running the generator twice with the same domain skips the append if the entry already exists.
Safety features

• --dry-run previews without writing

• Refuses to overwrite existing feature folders (bypass with --force)

• Rejects non-kebab-case input and reserved names

• Zero external dependencies — uses only Node.js built-ins

5. Proof: generating a Products page
The demo repo includes a Products page that was generated by the CLI and then enriched with realistic data:
npm run gen:dash-page -- productsAfter generation, the domain stub was replaced with typed product data (name, SKU, category, price, stock, status), and the columns were customised with number formatting, status badges, and stock-level highlighting.
